// C3: Physical sensing components
instance LiDARSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "LiDAR sensor mounted on the 1/10‑scale autonomous vehicle providing raw point‑cloud data"
    DTDFVocab:producedData LiDARPointCloudTransmitted
]

instance VehicleStateSensor : DTDFVocab:SensingComponent [
    base:desc "Vehicle state source (speed, position) collected via on‑board CAN bus"
    DTDFVocab:producedData VehicleStateTransmitted
]

// C4: Physical-to-virtual interaction (Data transmitted)
instance LiDARPointCloudTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom LiDARSensor
    base:desc "Transmission of raw LiDAR point‑cloud data from the Physical Twin to the Digital Twin over ROS2 topics"
]

instance VehicleStateTransmitted : DTDFVocab:DataTransmitted [
    DTDFVocab:producedFrom VehicleStateSensor
    base:desc "Transmission of vehicle state information from the Physical Twin to the Digital Twin over ROS2 topics"
]

// C10: Data instances
instance LiDARPointCloudData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Raw point‑cloud data used for clustering and object tracking"
    DTDFVocab:fromData LiDARPointCloudTransmitted
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataTranslationFE
]

instance VehicleStateData : DTDFVocab:Data [
    base:desc "Vehicle speed and position data used for ACC computation and monitoring"
    DTDFVocab:fromData VehicleStateTransmitted
    DTDFVocab:inputTo DataTranslationFE
]

// C11: Enablers (Functional Entities)
instance DataTranslationFE : DTDFVocab:Enabler [
    base:desc "Data Translation functional entity that serialises streams, aligns message types and performs unit conversions per ISO 23247"
    DTDFVocab:enables ComputationOffloadingService, DataMonitoringService
]

// C6: Services
instance ComputationOffloadingService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service that off‑loads the Adaptive Cruise Control algorithm to the cloud and returns the desired speed"
    DTDFVocab:provides DesiredSpeedInsight, SetSpeedAction
]

instance DataMonitoringService : DTDFVocab:Service [
    base:desc "Service that displays real‑time vehicle state, object tracks and projected driving path to the user interface"
    DTDFVocab:provides VehicleStateInsight, ObjectTracksInsight
]

// C17: Insights
instance DesiredSpeedInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insight representing the desired speed computed by the ACC model"
]

instance VehicleStateInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insight showing current vehicle speed and position"
]

instance ObjectTracksInsight : DTDFVocab:Insight [
    base:desc "Insight presenting detected object positions and trajectories from LiDAR clustering"
]

// C17: Actions
instance SetSpeedAction : DTDFVocab:Action [
    base:desc "Action to command the vehicle with the desired speed output from the ACC algorithm"
    DTDFVocab:IsAutomatic false
]

instance virtual_to_physical_interaction : DTDFVocab:VirtualToPhysical [
    base:desc "Commands generated by the Digital Twin (desired speed, ACC enable/disable, emergency‑braking command) are produced by the Control Panel FE in the User Entity, passed through the Data Translation FE for serialisation and unit conversion, and transmitted back to the Physical Twin over the same Wi‑Fi UDP channel. The Actuation FE on the Physical Twin receives these control messages and forwards the desired speed to the vehicle’s actuators (motor, steering servo). The documents do not detail specific command message formats, validation, authentication, conflict‑resolution policies, or explicit execution acknowledgements."
]

instance twinning_time_scale : DTDFVocab:TimeScale [
    base:desc "The twin requires clock synchronization between physical and digital components within 100 ms, as dictated by hardware limitations and safety‑critical vehicular standards. All ROS2 nodes exchange messages using DDS, which is configured to meet this sub‑100 ms bound, supporting the low end‑to‑end latency needed for data monitoring, computation offloading and remote management services."
]

instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The system follows the ISO 23247 reference architecture using an entity‑based constellation. Functional Entities are mapped to ROS2 packages; inter‑entity communication is handled by ROS2 DDS middleware, enabling real‑time data flow and control commands. Resource allocation is performed per entity on dedicated hardware, and the overall orchestration is achieved by the ROS2 launch system that starts the three packages together, forming a coherent digital twin system."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
    base:desc "Model fidelity is driven by the need for low end‑to‑end latency (≤100 ms) and safety‑critical operation. The ACC behavioural model is validated against real vehicle state and object tracking data obtained from the LiDAR clustering component. Uncertainty sources include sensor noise from LiDAR and vehicle state measurements; the Data Translation FE reduces systematic errors by performing unit conversion and message alignment. Validation is performed by visual inspection of real‑time 3D visualisation and by generating reports that compare predicted paths with actual vehicle trajectories. ROS2 communication integrity and UDP packet loss are mitigated by the required 100 ms clock synchronization and by monitoring data timestamps. Quality assurance includes a publicly available demonstration video and compliance with ISO 23247 functional entities."
]

instance dt_technical_connection : DTDFVocab:TechnicalConnection [
    base:desc "The DTS uses a hybrid communication stack: intra‑entity software components are coupled via a ROS 2 network, while communication between the three ISO 23247 entities (Physical Twin, Digital Twin, User) is carried out over a Wi‑Fi network using UDP. The design requires low end‑to‑end latency (the system is described as needing “low end‑to‑end latency communication”) and a clock‑synchronisation accuracy of 100 ms for safety‑critical operation. No bandwidth figures, redundancy mechanisms, or security protocols (e.g., encryption, authentication) are specified in the provided text."
]

instance dt_hosting_deployment : DTDFVocab:Deployment [
    base:desc "The ACC functionality is off‑loaded from the on‑board ECU to an external compute platform described only as “the cloud”. Each functional element is packaged as a ROS 2 package (one or more nodes) and deployed on separate hardware components corresponding to the three entities. The documents do not give concrete details on storage capacity, compute specifications, scalability approaches, deployment models (e.g., containerisation, edge vs. cloud), or availability/reliability guarantees."
]

instance standardization : DTDFVocab:Standardization [
    base:desc "The automotive digital twin system adheres to the ISO 23247 reference architecture, structuring functionality into the Data Collection and Device Control Entity, Digital Twin Entity, User Entity and their associated Functional Entities. Safety aspects are aligned with ISO 26262, which the authors recommend promoting to a first‑class citizen in automotive DT standards. Interoperability and data exchange are implemented using OPC Unified Architecture as defined in IEC 62541 for the Data Translation functional entity. The software components are realized as ROS 2 packages, complying with the ROS 2 middleware specifications, and the overall design acknowledges the AUTOSAR automotive software architecture for hardware‑agnostic component deployment."
]